Stanbic IBTC Holdings Plc has confirmed the payment of the sum of N2.5 billion to Mr Patrick Akinkuotu and Longterm Global Capital Limited in response to a Supreme Court ruling. The group informed the Nigerian Stock Exchange and the public that the full payment has been made, after almost 10 years of protracted litigation. In a statement signed by the Company Secretary, Chidi Okezie, Stanbic IBTC also assured its stakeholders that the outcome of the litigation will neither ’affect the companys liquidity nor its profitability in the long run. OVER 5,000 NIGERIAN MEN HAVE  OVERCOME POOR BEDROOM PERFORMANCE SYNDROME DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY. CLICK HERE TO KNOW MORE Recall that in 2010, the Federal High Court was the first to rule in favour of Longterm Global Capital and Patrick Akinkuotu, but Stanbic IBTC Bank went to the Court of Appeal and up to the Supreme Court but was dismissed. Mr Patrick Akinkuotu and his company (Longterm Global Capital Limited) obtained overdraft facilities worth N600 million and N650 million from the bank between April and July 2007. The facilities were for a term of 365 days with an option of rollover. Thereafter, Akinkuotu requested that the facilities granted to himself and his company be merged. The request was then obliged by the bank. The facilities were secured with the equity stakes both Akinkuoto and Longterm Global Capital Limited held in some companies.  FRC Suspends Atedo Peterside, David-Borha others over alleged accounts infractions Court grants interim forfeiture of Patience Jonathan’s N350m SEC suspends Stanbic IBTC N20bn rights issue Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin